2️⃣ Build the Internal Scoring Logic (Deterministic Layer)

Before any AI model, you must have rule-based scoring.

Example:

if (support_ticket_volume > 150 && avg_response_time > 12) {
   core_problem = "Customer Service Bottleneck"
   priority_score = 9
}

if (inventory_sync_manual === true && oversell_incidents > 2) {
   core_problem = "Inventory Chaos"
   priority_score = 8
}

if (cart_abandonment_rate > 65) {
   core_problem = "Revenue Leakage"
   priority_score = 7
}

Then:

sort by priority_score desc
pick highest

This ensures stability before LLM exists.

3️⃣ Build Recommendation Mapping Table

Core Problem → Sprint Template

Core Problem	Sprint
Customer Service Bottleneck	Automation Sprint
Inventory Chaos	Inventory Sync Sprint
High CAC	Retention Sprint
Low Repeat Rate	Lifecycle Optimization Sprint

This makes output predictable.

4️⃣ Create Editable Content Blocks (Figma Safe)

Right now you are in Figma-only mode.

So store:

Phase titles

Deliverables

KPIs

Risk registry

Investment ranges

As static JSON objects inside the frontend.

Later you swap static JSON → API response.

Do NOT hardcode text into components.
Bind everything to a data object.

5️⃣ Add Confidence Layer

You need this immediately:

"confidence_score": 82

Calculated from:

Data completeness %

Consistency of answers

Severity score gap between top 2 problems

If gap is small → confidence lower.

This makes your system feel intelligent.

6️⃣ Add “Why This, Why Not Others” Logic

Every recommendation must explain:

Why chosen

Why not the others yet

This builds trust.

Example:

We are not recommending platform migration because current stack is sufficient and operational inefficiency is the root cause.

That logic layer is critical.